abstract: The battle for momentum in the two states could prove pivotal. Here’s how the candidates are making their pitches.

abstract: Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren probably both can’t squeeze through.
snippet: Bernie Sanders and Elizabeth Warren probably both can’t squeeze through.
lead_paragraph: In the Democratic presidential primary, two states have had their say — two small, unrepresentative, delegate-poor states. Yet those elections — or whatever one calls what happened in Iowa — have reset the contest, vitalizing some campaigns (Klomentum!) while leaving others on life support. Three wound up in the morgue.

abstract: Democratic presidential candidate Amy Klobuchar says she no longer believes English should be the national language of the U.S., disavowing a vote she took more than a decade ago as she tries to build support in a state where Hispanics make up a critical constituency.
snippet: Democratic presidential candidate Amy Klobuchar says she no longer believes English should be the national language of the U.S., disavowing a vote she took more than a decade ago as she tries to build support in a state where Hispanics make up a c...
lead_paragraph: LAS VEGAS — Democratic presidential candidate Amy Klobuchar says she no longer believes English should be the national language of the U.S., disavowing a vote she took more than a decade ago as she tries to build support in a state where Hispanics make up a critical constituency.
headline_main: Klobuchar Shifts on Immigration Before Nevada Caucuses
headline_print_headline: Klobuchar Shifts on Immigration Before Nevada Caucuses

abstract: The New York City mayor, who was briefly a presidential candidate himself, is scheduled to campaign with Mr. Sanders in Nevada ahead of the caucuses there next week.
snippet: The New York City mayor, who was briefly a presidential candidate himself, is scheduled to campaign with Mr. Sanders in Nevada ahead of the caucuses there next week.
lead_paragraph: Mayor Bill de Blasio of New York, whose brief presidential campaign failed to get off the ground last year, endorsed Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont for the Democratic nomination on Friday.

abstract: As the Democratic presidential race hurtles toward Nevada, candidates in the still-crowded field are jumping into their first test in a racially diverse state with solid union muscle and shaky plans for a presidential caucus.
snippet: As the Democratic presidential race hurtles toward Nevada, candidates in the still-crowded field are jumping into their first test in a racially diverse state with solid union muscle and shaky plans for a presidential caucus.
lead_paragraph: LAS VEGAS — As the Democratic presidential race hurtles toward Nevada, candidates in the still-crowded field are jumping into their first test in a racially diverse state with solid union muscle and shaky plans for a presidential caucus.
headline_main: Diversity Test: 2020 Democrats Seek Their Fortunes in Nevada
headline_print_headline: Diversity Test: 2020 Democrats Seek Their Fortunes in Nevada

abstract: Facebook Inc said on Friday it was allowing U.S.-based political candidates to run branded content on its social networking platforms, but the content would not be cataloged in its advertising library.
snippet: Facebook Inc said on Friday it was allowing U.S.-based political candidates to run branded content on its social networking platforms, but the content would not be cataloged in its advertising library.
lead_paragraph: (Reuters) - Facebook Inc said on Friday it was allowing U.S.-based political candidates to run branded content on its social networking platforms, but the content would not be cataloged in its advertising library.
headline_main: Facebook Allows U.S. Political Candidates to Run Sponsored Content
headline_print_headline: Facebook Allows U.S. Political Candidates to Run Sponsored Content

abstract: No winner has been declared in the Iowa Democratic caucuses. The results were so riddled with errors that we may never know what really happened.

abstract: A crucial question for the Vermont senator has always been whether he can expand his coalition. In a race this crowded, it’s unclear whether he even needs to do so.

abstract: A whipsaw week of charged decisions by the Justice Department, some favored by the president and others not, has bewildered much of Washington.
snippet: A whipsaw week of charged decisions by the Justice Department, some favored by the president and others not, has bewildered much of Washington.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When President Trump learned that the Justice Department was dropping a case against a former F.B.I. official whom he considered one of his longtime enemies, his immediate response was anger. As he flipped on the television Friday and watched how the story was being covered, that anger only mounted.
